[1] Washington State (Island County)
Date: Thu 7 Jun 2012
Source: The Whidbey Examiner [edited]
http://www.whidbeyexaminer.com/main.asp?SectionID=1&SubSectionID=1&ArticleID=7833


This past week 3 more cases of pertussis were reported at Coupeville Elementary School, bringing the total to 10 students and an adult. Island County and school health officials say that more reports of cases of this contagious disease are possible at the 350 student school. The county health department reports at least 42 confirmed and probable cases of pertussis, also called whooping cough, on Whidbey and Camano islands as of 5 Jun 2012. 8 of the local students who contracted the disease had been vaccinated against pertussis, school nurse Tina Lewis said.

It is very likely most adults have not received the pertussis vaccine for adolescents and adults. Everyone over age 12 should have received at least one dose of the Tdap [or DTaP; tetanus, diphtheria, pertussis], said Island County health officer Roger Case. The immunization booster is required for school attendance for those over 11 years old. "It is estimated that less than 10 per cent of the population has actually received the Tdap immunization," Case said.

Before the development of the pertussis vaccine, the United States typically saw about 200 000 cases a year, she said. In 2010, 27 550 cases of whooping cough were reported across the nation, the highest number since 1959, she said.

The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has found that immunization reduces the odds of contracting pertussis, especially for children. "Children who never received any doses of DTaP vaccine face odds of having whooping cough at least 8 times higher than children who received all 5 doses of the vaccine," Patti said.

[byline: Elisabeth Murray]

