[9] Iowa
Date: Thu 31 May 2012
Source: Waterloo-Cedar Falls Courier [edited]
http://wcfcourier.com/news/local/more-pertussis-cases-reported-in-county/article_f7e2cc33-a86d-586c-ab02-a4fb634b50c3.html


Pertussis, or whooping cough, continues to spread through the Cedar Valley and across the state. Black Hawk County has seen 13 cases in April and May [2012], according to Kaitlin Emrich, disease surveillance program manager with the county health department. 4 of those were reported at East High School and another 4 at Hoover Middle School. However, numbers have slowed down the past few weeks. "I don't know if that's because schools are letting out (for the summer), and kids are outside," Emrich said. "It's less likely to spread in an outdoor environment."

Communicable disease staff has been working closely with school nurses to track down infected persons and alert those with whom they've been in contact, she said. As additional people display symptoms, health officials follow up to make sure they are tested and receive treatment if necessary. They've also been educating health care providers.

According to the IDPH [Iowa Department of Public Health], the past 5 years have seen an average of 91 cases of pertussis compared to 270 cases in 2012 as of 25 May 2012. That's a nearly 200 per cent increase, though no pertussis-related deaths have been reported to IDPH in 2012. Historically, pertussis has been cyclical, with increased activity observed every 3 to 5 years.

Around north east Iowa in 2012, 33 investigations have been completed in Fayette County, 8 in Cerro Gordo, 3 in Buchanan, and 4 in Delaware. Polk County has logged 55 cases, and Scott, along the south eastern border with Illinois, has reported 64.

[byline: Tina Hinz]

