[11] Kansas (Johnson County)
Date: Mon 28 May 2012
Source: KCUR [edited]
http://www.kcur.org/post/johnson-county-works-contain-whooping-cough-outbreak


Johnson County, Kansas is in the midst of a whooping cough outbreak. It's not as bad as in Washington State, where they've declared an epidemic of the disease, also known as pertussis. But health workers and schools in the region have been taking extra steps to get a handle on the disease.

Nancy Tausz, a disease specialist with the county, says the outbreak surfaced in mid-April 2012. "With that many cases come in, and continually, you know something other than just the norm is happening," Tausz says. The county is now investigating more than 130 cases of the disease. Tausz says at first, it was concentrated in the southern part of the county. "The ages we saw at the beginning were 5th grade and 6th grade," Tausz says. "And then started expanding from 5th grade to 8th grade."

[byline: Elana Gordon]

